   <ContentDescription audience="Patients" language="en">Positron emission tomography (PET) scan; drawing shows a child lying on table that slides through the PET scanner. </ContentDescription>
  </ContentDescriptions>
  <Captions>
   <MediaCaption audience="Patients" language="en">Positron emission tomography (PET) scan. The child lies on a table that slides through the PET scanner. The head rest and white strap help the child lie still.  A small amount of radioactive glucose (sugar) is injected into the child's vein, and a scanner makes a picture of where the glucose is being used in the body.  Cancer cells show up brighter in the picture because they take up more glucose than normal cells do. </MediaCaption>
